SIMPLE: upset
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Upset
<hw>Up*set"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To set
up; to put upright.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧With sail on mast
<xex>upset</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>R. of Brunne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To thicken and shorten, as a heated
piece of iron, by hammering on the end.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To
shorten (a tire) in the process of resetting, originally by cutting it
and hammering on the ends.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To overturn, overthrow, or overset; <as>as, to
<ex>upset</ex> a carriage; to <ex>upset</ex> an argument.</as></def>
⟦ldquo⟧Determined somehow to <xex>upset</xex> the situation.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Mrs. Humphry Ward.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To disturb the self-possession of; to disorder the
nerves of; to make ill; <as>as, the fright <ex>upset</ex>
her</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Basketwork)</fld> <def>To turn upwards the outer
ends of (stakes) so as to make a foundation for the side of a basket or
the like; also, to form (the side) in this manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Upset</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Upset
<hw>Up*set"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become upset.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Upset</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Upset
<hw>Up"set`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Set up; fixed;
determined; -- used chiefly or only in the phrase <xex>upset
price</xex>; that is, the price fixed upon as the minimum for property
offered in a public sale, or, in an auction, the price at which property
is set up or started by the auctioneer, and the lowest price at which it
will be sold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After a solemn pause, Mr. Glossin offered the <qex>upset</qex>
price for the lands and barony of Ellangowan.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Upset</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Upset
<hw>Up"set`</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of upsetting, or the state
of being upset; an overturn; <as>as, the wagon had an
<ex>upset</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Upsetting</ent>⟦br⟧
